This is because SourceTree runs 'git reset <file>'. This works perfectly fine in every case other than before the first commit, where it reports
{noformat}
fatal: Failed to resolve 'HEAD' as a valid ref.
{noformat}

In fact in this case we should be using 'git rm --cached'. You can't use this for any other case than newly added files, since for existing files it removes them from the repository. Typical usability issues from git...

Currently I don't use the merge feature of source-tree but do merges using the command line using 

{code}
git merge <branchName>
{code}

Sourcetree currently forces me to select a commit, which IMHO is quite inconvenient.

To search for an unmodified file (e.g. to initiate blame / log), you currently have to switch the filter to 'Show All' before typing in the filter box. Ideally it would be nice to be able to do this faster while still keeping the default view on 'Show Pending'.

@aras_p requested on Twitter that the criteria be automatically switched to 'Show All' when you start typing in the filter box. However, sometimes people want to filter the current view, even the Show Pending view (it's faster to do this than to flip over to 'Show All' because it doesn't need a new query), so this won't be what everyone wants.

Nevertheless, a faster way to find a file regardless of status would be very useful.
